{"input": "arr = [3, 5, 7, 2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 11]", "output": "True"}, {"input": "arr = [5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35, 40, 45, 50, 55, 60, 65, 70, 75]", "output": "False"}], "query": "You are an expert Python programmer. You will be given a question (problem specification) and will generate a correct Python program that matches the specification and passes all tests.\n\n### Question:\nGiven an integer array arr, return true if there are three consecutive odd numbers in the array. Otherwise, return false.\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: arr = [2,6,4,1]\nOutput: false\nExplanation: There are no three consecutive odds.\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: arr = [1,2,34,3,4,5,7,23,12]\nOutput: true\nExplanation: [5,7,23] are three consecutive odds.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= arr.length <= 1000\n1 <= arr[i] <= 1000\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def threeConsecutiveOdds(self, arr: List[int]) -> bool:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def threeConsecutiveOdds(self, arr: List[int]) -> bool:\n        # Iterate through the array with a window of size 3\n        for i in range(len(arr) - 2):\n            # Check if the current element, the next element, and the one after that are all odd\n            if arr[i] % 2 == 1 and arr[i + 1] % 2 == 1 and arr[i + 2] % 2 == 1:\n                return True\n        return False\n```\n\nThis solution iterates through the array and checks each group of three consecutive numbers to see if they are all odd. If such a group is found, it returns `True`. If the loop completes without finding any such group, it returns `False`. This approach ensures that the solution is efficient with a time complexity of O(n), where n is the length of the array.", "estimated_date": 1597536000000}